# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: authenticated-encryption
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Many (but not all) AE schemes allow the message to contain "associated data" (AD) which is not made confidential, but is integrity protected (i.e., readable, but tamperevident).
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] A typical example is the header of a network packet that contains its destination address.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] To properly route the packet, all intermediate nodes in the message path need to know the destination, but for security reasons they cannot possess the secret key.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Schemes that allow associated data provide authenticated encryption with associated data, or **AEAD**.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] The *header* part is intended to provide authenticity and integrity protection for networking or storage metadata for which confidentiality is unnecessary, but authenticity is desired.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] The need for authenticated encryption emerged from the observation that securely combining separate *confidentiality* and *authentication* block cipher operation modes could be error prone and difficult.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] This was confirmed by a number of practical attacks introduced into production protocols and applications by incorrect implementation, or lack of authentication.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Around the year 2000, a number of efforts evolved around the notion of standardizing modes that ensured correct implementation.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] In particular, strong interest in possibly secure modes was sparked by the publication of Charanjit Jutla's integrity-aware CBC and integrity-aware parallelizable, IAPM, modes in 2000 (see OCB and chronology).
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Six different authenticated encryption modes (namely offset codebook mode 2.0, OCB 2.0; Key Wrap; counter with CBC-MAC, CCM; encrypt then authenticate then translate, EAX; encrypt-then-MAC, EtM; and Galois/counter mode, GCM) have been standardized in ISO/IEC 19772:2009.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] More authenticated encryption methods were developed in response to NIST solicitation.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Sponge functions can be used in duplex mode to provide authenticated encryption.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Katz and Yung investigated the notion under the name "unforgeable encryption" and proved it implies security against chosen ciphertext attacks.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] In 2013, the CAESAR competition was announced to encourage design of authenticated encryption modes.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] In 2015, ChaCha20-Poly1305 is added as an alternative AE construction to GCM in IETF protocols.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Authenticated encryption with associated data (AEAD) is a variant of AE that allows the message to include "associated data" (AD, additional non-confidential information, a.k.a.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] A recipient can check the integrity of both the associated data and the confidential information in a message.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] AD is useful, for example, in network packets where the header should be visible for routing, but the payload needs to be confidential, and both need integrity and authenticity.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] The notion of AEAD was formalized by Rogaway (2002).
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] AE was originally designed primarily to provide the ciphertext integrity: successful validation of an authentication tag by Alice using her symmetric key KA indicates that the message was not tampered with by an adversary Mallory that does not possess the KA.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] The AE schemes usually do not provide the **key commitment**, a guarantee that the decryption would fail for any other key.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] As of 2021, most existing AE schemes (including the very popular GCM) allow some messages to be decrypted without an error using more than just the (correct) KA; while the plaintext decrypted using a second (wrong) key KM will be incorrect, the authentication tag would still match the new plaintext.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Since crafting a message with such property requires Mallory to already possess both KA and KM, the issue might appear to be one of a purely academic interest.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] However, under special circumstances, practical attacks can be mounted against vulnerable implementations.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] For this dictionary attack to succeed, Mallory also needs an ability to distinguish successful decryption by Alice from an unsuccessful one, due, for example, to a poor protocol design or implementation turning Alice's side into an oracle.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Naturally, this attack cannot be mounted at all when the keys are generated randomly.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Key commitment was originally studied in the 2010s by Abdalla et al. and Farshim et al. under the name "robust encryption".
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] To mitigate the attack described above without removing the "oracle", a *key-committing AEAD* that does not allow this type of crafted messages to exist can be used.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] AEGIS is an example of fast (if the AES instruction set is present), key-committing AEAD.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] It is possible to add key-commitment to an existing AEAD scheme.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Misuse-resistant authenticated encryption (MRAE) has the additional property that reusing the same nonce for several messages does not allow an attacker to recover the plaintext.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] MRAE was formalized in 2006 by Phillip Rogaway and Thomas Shrimpton.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] One example of a MRAE algorithm is AES-GCM-SIV.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] The plaintext is first encrypted, then a MAC is produced based on the resulting ciphertext.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] The ciphertext and its MAC are sent together.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] ETM is the standard method according to ISO/IEC 19772:2009.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] It is the only method which can reach the highest definition of security in AE, but this can only be achieved when the MAC used is "strongly unforgeable".
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] In November 2014, TLS and DTLS received extensions for EtM with RFC 7366.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Various EtM ciphersuites exist for SSHv2 as well (e.g., hmac-sha1-etm@openssh.com).
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] A MAC is produced based on the plaintext, and the plaintext is encrypted without the MAC.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] The plaintext's MAC and the ciphertext are sent together.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Even though the E&M approach has not been proved to be strongly unforgeable in itself, it is possible to apply some minor modifications to SSH to make it strongly unforgeable despite the approach.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] A MAC is produced based on the plaintext, then the plaintext and MAC are together encrypted to produce a ciphertext based on both.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] The ciphertext (containing an encrypted MAC) is sent.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Until TLS 1.2, all available SSL/TLS cipher suites were MtE.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] MtE has not been proven to be strongly unforgeable in itself.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] The SSL/TLS implementation has been proven to be strongly unforgeable by Krawczyk who showed that SSL/TLS was, in fact, secure because of the encoding used alongside the MtE mechanism.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] However, Krawczyk's proof contains flawed assumptions about the randomness of the initialization vector (IV).
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] The 2011 BEAST attack exploited the non-random chained IV and broke all CBC algorithms in TLS 1.0 and under.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] In addition, deeper analysis of SSL/TLS modeled the protection as MAC-then-pad-then-encrypt, i.e. the plaintext is first padded to the block size of the encryption function.
[src:authenticated-encryption/authenticated-encryption] Padding errors often result in the detectable errors on the recipient's side, which in turn lead to padding oracle attacks, such as Lucky Thirteen.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] In cryptography, a **block cipher mode of operation** is an algorithm that uses a block cipher to provide information security such as confidentiality or authenticity.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] A block cipher by itself is only suitable for the secure cryptographic transformation (encryption or decryption) of one fixed-length group of bits called a block.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] A mode of operation describes how to repeatedly apply a cipher's single-block operation to securely transform amounts of data larger than a block.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Most modes require a unique binary sequence, often called an initialization vector (IV), for each encryption operation.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The IV must be non-repeating, and for some modes must also be random.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The initialization vector is used to ensure that distinct ciphertexts are produced even when the same plaintext is encrypted multiple times independently with the same key.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Block ciphers may be capable of operating on more than one block size, but during transformation the block size is always fixed.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Block cipher modes operate on whole blocks and require that the final data fragment be padded to a full block if it is smaller than the current block size.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] There are, however, modes that do not require padding because they effectively use a block cipher as a stream cipher.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Historically, encryption modes have been studied extensively in regard to their error propagation properties under various scenarios of data modification.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Later development regarded integrity protection as an entirely separate cryptographic goal.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Some modern modes of operation combine confidentiality and authenticity in an efficient way, and are known as authenticated encryption modes.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The earliest modes of operation, ECB, CBC, OFB, and CFB (see below for all), date back to 1981 and were specified in FIPS 81, *DES Modes of Operation*.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] In 2001, the US National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) revised its list of approved modes of operation by including AES as a block cipher and adding CTR mode in SP800-38A, *Recommendation for Block Cipher Modes of Operation*.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Finally, in January, 2010, NIST added XTS-AES in SP800-38E, *Recommendation for Block Cipher Modes of Operation: The XTS-AES Mode for Confidentiality on Storage Devices*.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Other confidentiality modes exist which have not been approved by NIST.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] For example, CTS is ciphertext stealing mode and available in many popular cryptographic libraries.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The block cipher modes ECB, CBC, OFB, CFB, CTR, and XTS provide confidentiality, but they do not protect against accidental modification or malicious tampering.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Modification or tampering can be detected with a separate message authentication code such as CBC-MAC, or a digital signature.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The cryptographic community recognized the need for dedicated integrity assurances and NIST responded with HMAC, CMAC, and GMAC.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The cryptographic community observed that compositing (combining) a confidentiality mode with an authenticity mode could be difficult and error prone.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] They therefore began to supply modes which combined confidentiality and data integrity into a single cryptographic primitive (an encryption algorithm).
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] These combined modes are referred to as authenticated encryption, AE or "authenc".
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Examples of AE modes are CCM (SP800-38C), GCM (SP800-38D), CWC, EAX, IAPM, and OCB.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Modes of operation are defined by a number of national and internationally recognized standards bodies.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Notable standards organizations include NIST, ISO (with ISO/IEC 10116), the IEC, the IEEE, ANSI, and the IETF.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] An initialization vector (IV) or starting variable (SV) is a block of bits that is used by several modes to randomize the encryption and hence to produce distinct ciphertexts even if the same plaintext is encrypted multiple times under the identical key.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] An initialization vector has different security requirements than a key, so the IV usually does not need to be secret.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] For most block cipher modes it is important that an initialization vector is never reused under the same key, i.e. it must be a cryptographic nonce.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Many block cipher modes have stronger requirements, such as the IV must be random or pseudorandom.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Some block ciphers have particular problems with certain initialization vectors, such as all zero IV generating no encryption (for some keys).
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] It is recommended to review relevant IV requirements for the particular block cipher mode in relevant specification, for example SP800-38A.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] For CBC and CFB, reusing an IV leaks some information about the first block of plaintext, and about any common prefix shared by the two messages.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] For OFB and CTR, reusing an IV causes key bitstream re-use, which breaks security.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] This can be seen because both modes effectively create a bitstream that is XORed with the plaintext, and this bitstream is dependent on the key and IV only.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] In CBC mode, the IV must be unpredictable (random or pseudorandom) at encryption time; in particular, the (previously) common practice of re-using the last ciphertext block of a message as the IV for the next message is insecure (for example, this method was used by SSL 2.0).
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] If an attacker knows the IV (or the previous block of ciphertext) before the next plaintext is specified, they can check their guess about plaintext of some block that was encrypted with the same key before (this is known as the TLS CBC IV attack).
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] For some keys, an all-zero initialization vector may generate some block cipher modes (CFB-8, OFB-8) to get the internal state stuck at all-zero.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] For CFB-8, an all-zero IV and an all-zero plaintext, causes 1/256 of keys to generate no encryption, plaintext is returned as ciphertext.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] For OFB-8, using all zero initialization vector will generate no encryption for 1/256 of keys.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] OFB-8 encryption returns the plaintext unencrypted for affected keys.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Some modes (such as AES-SIV and AES-GCM-SIV) are built to be more nonce-misuse resistant, i.e. resilient to scenarios in which the randomness generation is faulty or under the control of the attacker.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] A block cipher works on units of a fixed size (known as a *block size*), but messages come in a variety of lengths.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] So some modes (namely ECB and CBC) require that the final block be padded before encryption.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Slightly more complex is the original DES method, which is to add a single one bit, followed by enough zero bits to fill out the block; if the message ends on a block boundary, a whole padding block will be added.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Most sophisticated are CBC-specific schemes such as ciphertext stealing or residual block termination, which do not cause any extra ciphertext, at the expense of some additional complexity.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Schneier and Ferguson suggest two possibilities, both simple: append a byte with value 128 (hex 80), followed by as many zero bytes as needed to fill the last block, or pad the last block with *n* bytes all with value *n*.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] CFB, OFB and CTR modes do not require any special measures to handle messages whose lengths are not multiples of the block size, since the modes work by XORing the plaintext with the output of the block cipher.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The last partial block of plaintext is XORed with the first few bytes of the last keystream block, producing a final ciphertext block that is the same size as the final partial plaintext block.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] This characteristic of stream ciphers makes them suitable for applications that require the encrypted ciphertext data to be the same size as the original plaintext data, and for applications that transmit data in streaming form where it is inconvenient to add padding bytes.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] A number of modes of operation have been designed to combine secrecy and authentication in a single cryptographic primitive.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Examples of such modes are, RIV, McOE, IACBC, IAPM, Ascon, OCB, EAX, CWC, CCM, AES-GCM-SIV, and GCM.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Authenticated encryption modes are classified as single-pass modes or double-pass modes.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] In addition, some modes also allow for the authentication of unencrypted associated data, and these are called AEAD (authenticated encryption with associated data) schemes.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] For example, EAX mode is a double-pass AEAD scheme while OCB mode is single-pass.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Galois/counter mode (GCM) combines the well-known counter mode of encryption with the new Galois mode of authentication.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The key feature is the ease of parallel computation of the Galois field multiplication used for authentication.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] This feature permits higher throughput than encryption algorithms.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] GCM is defined for block ciphers with a block size of 128 bits.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Galois message authentication code (GMAC) is an authentication-only variant of the GCM which can form an incremental message authentication code.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Both GCM and GMAC can accept initialization vectors of arbitrary length.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] GCM can take full advantage of parallel processing and implementing GCM can make efficient use of an instruction pipeline or a hardware pipeline.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The CBC mode of operation incurs pipeline stalls that hamper its efficiency and performance.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Like in CTR, blocks are numbered sequentially, and then this block number is combined with an IV and encrypted with a block cipher E, usually AES.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The result of this encryption is then XORed with the plaintext to produce the ciphertext.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Like all counter modes, this is essentially a stream cipher, and so it is essential that a different IV is used for each stream that is encrypted.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The ciphertext blocks are considered coefficients of a polynomial which is then evaluated at a key-dependent point H, using finite field arithmetic.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The result is then encrypted, producing an authentication tag that can be used to verify the integrity of the data.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The encrypted text then contains the IV, ciphertext, and authentication tag.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Synthetic initialization vector (SIV) is a nonce-misuse resistant block cipher mode.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] SIV synthesizes an internal IV using the pseudorandom function S2V.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] SIV encrypts the S2V output and the plaintext using AES-CTR, keyed with the encryption key (K2).
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] SIV can support external nonce-based authenticated encryption, in which case one of the authenticated data fields is utilized for this purpose.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] RFC5297 specifies that for interoperability purposes the last authenticated data field should be used external nonce.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Owing to the use of two keys, the authentication key K1 and encryption key K2, naming schemes for SIV AEAD-variants may lead to some confusion; for example AEAD_AES_SIV_CMAC_256 refers to AES-SIV with two AES-128 keys and **not** AES-256.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] AES-GCM-SIV is a mode of operation for the Advanced Encryption Standard which provides similar performance to Galois/counter mode as well as misuse resistance in the event of the reuse of a cryptographic nonce.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The construction is defined in RFC 8452.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] AES-GCM-SIV synthesizes the internal IV.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] It derives a hash of the additional authenticated data and plaintext using the POLYVAL Galois hash function.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The hash is then encrypted an AES-key, and used as authentication tag and AES-CTR initialization vector.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Many modes of operation have been defined.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The purpose of cipher modes is to mask patterns which exist in encrypted data, as illustrated in the description of the weakness of ECB.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Different cipher modes mask patterns by cascading outputs from the cipher block or other globally deterministic variables into the subsequent cipher block.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The simplest of the encryption modes is the **electronic codebook** (ECB) mode (named after conventional physical codebooks).
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The message is divided into blocks, and each block is encrypted separately.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] ECB is not recommended for use in cryptographic protocols: the disadvantage of this method is a lack of diffusion, wherein it fails to hide data patterns when it encrypts identical plaintext blocks into identical ciphertext blocks.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] A striking example of the degree to which ECB can leave plaintext data patterns in the ciphertext can be seen when ECB mode is used to encrypt a bitmap image which contains large areas of uniform color.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] While the color of each individual pixel has supposedly been encrypted, the overall image may still be discerned, as the pattern of identically colored pixels in the original remains visible in the encrypted version.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] ECB mode can also make protocols without integrity protection even more susceptible to replay attacks, since each block gets decrypted in exactly the same way.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Ehrsam, Meyer, Smith and Tuchman invented the cipher block chaining (CBC) mode of operation in 1976.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] In CBC mode, each block of plaintext is XORed with the previous ciphertext block before being encrypted.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] This way, each ciphertext block depends on all plaintext blocks processed up to that point.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] To make each message unique, an initialization vector must be used in the first block.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] CBC has been the most commonly used mode of operation.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Its main drawbacks are that encryption is sequential (i.e., it cannot be parallelized), and that the message must be padded to a multiple of the cipher block size.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] One way to handle this last issue is through the method known as ciphertext stealing.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Note that a one-bit change in a plaintext or initialization vector (IV) affects all following ciphertext blocks.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Decrypting with the incorrect IV causes the first block of plaintext to be corrupt but subsequent plaintext blocks will be correct.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] This is because each block is XORed with the ciphertext of the previous block, not the plaintext, so one does not need to decrypt the previous block before using it as the IV for the decryption of the current one.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] This means that a plaintext block can be recovered from two adjacent blocks of ciphertext.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] As a consequence, decryption *can* be parallelized.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Note that a one-bit change to the ciphertext causes complete corruption of the corresponding block of plaintext, and inverts the corresponding bit in the following block of plaintext, but the rest of the blocks remain intact.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] This peculiarity is exploited in different padding oracle attacks, such as POODLE.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The *propagating cipher block chaining* or *plaintext cipher-block chaining* mode was designed to cause small changes in the ciphertext to propagate indefinitely when decrypting, as well as when encrypting.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] In PCBC mode, each block of plaintext is XORed with both the previous plaintext block and the previous ciphertext block before being encrypted.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Like with CBC mode, an initialization vector is used in the first block.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Unlike CBC, decrypting PCBC with the incorrect IV (initialization vector) causes all blocks of plaintext to be corrupt.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] PCBC is used in Kerberos v4 and WASTE, most notably, but otherwise is not common.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] On a message encrypted in PCBC mode, if two adjacent ciphertext blocks are exchanged, this does not affect the decryption of subsequent blocks.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] For this reason, PCBC is not used in Kerberos v5.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The *cipher feedback* (CFB) mode, in its simplest form uses the entire output of the block cipher.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] In this variation, it is very similar to CBC, turning a block cipher into a self-synchronizing stream cipher.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] NIST SP800-38A defines CFB with a bit-width.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] *The CFB mode also requires an integer parameter, denoted s, such that 1 ≤ s ≤ b.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] In the specification of the CFB mode below, each plaintext segment (Pj) and ciphertext segment (Cj) consists of s bits.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] These modes will truncate the output of the underlying block cipher.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] CFB-1 is considered self synchronizing and resilient to loss of ciphertext; "When the 1-bit CFB mode is used, then the synchronization is automatically restored b+1 positions after the inserted or deleted bit.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] For other values of s in the CFB mode, and for the other confidentiality modes in this recommendation, the synchronization must be restored externally." (NIST SP800-38A).
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] 1-bit loss in a 128-bit-wide block cipher like AES will render 129 invalid bits before emitting valid bits.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] CFB may also self synchronize in some special cases other than those specified.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] For example, a one bit change in CFB-128 with an underlying 128 bit block cipher, will re-synchronize after two blocks.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Like CBC mode, changes in the plaintext propagate forever in the ciphertext, and encryption cannot be parallelized.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Also like CBC, decryption can be parallelized.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] CFB, OFB and CTR share two advantages over CBC mode: the block cipher is only ever used in the encrypting direction, and the message does not need to be padded to a multiple of the cipher block size (though ciphertext stealing can also be used for CBC mode to make padding unnecessary).
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The *output feedback* (OFB) mode makes a block cipher into a synchronous stream cipher.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] It generates keystream blocks, which are then XORed with the plaintext blocks to get the ciphertext.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Just as with other stream ciphers, flipping a bit in the ciphertext produces a flipped bit in the plaintext at the same location.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] This property allows many error-correcting codes to function normally even when applied before encryption.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Each output feedback block cipher operation depends on all previous ones, and so cannot be performed in parallel.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] However, because the plaintext or ciphertext is only used for the final XOR, the block cipher operations may be performed in advance, allowing the final step to be performed in parallel once the plaintext or ciphertext is available.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] It is possible to obtain an OFB mode keystream by using CBC mode with a constant string of zeroes as input.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] This can be useful, because it allows the usage of fast hardware implementations of CBC mode for OFB mode encryption.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Using OFB mode with a partial block as feedback like CFB mode reduces the average cycle length by a factor of 232 or more.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] A mathematical model proposed by Davies and Parkin and substantiated by experimental results showed that only with full feedback an average cycle length near to the obtainable maximum can be achieved.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] For this reason, support for truncated feedback was removed from the specification of OFB.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Like OFB, counter mode turns a block cipher into a stream cipher.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] It generates the next keystream block by encrypting successive values of a "counter".
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The counter can be any function which produces a sequence which is guaranteed not to repeat for a long time, although an actual increment-by-one counter is the simplest and most popular.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] The usage of a simple deterministic input function used to be controversial; critics argued that "deliberately exposing a cryptosystem to a known systematic input represents an unnecessary risk".
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] However, today CTR mode is widely accepted, and any problems are considered a weakness of the underlying block cipher, which is expected to be secure regardless of systemic bias in its input.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Along with CBC, CTR mode is one of two block cipher modes recommended by Niels Ferguson and Bruce Schneier.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] CTR mode was introduced by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman in 1979.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] CTR mode has similar characteristics to OFB, but also allows a random-access property during decryption.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] CTR mode is well suited to operate on a multi-processor machine, where blocks can be encrypted in parallel.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Furthermore, it does not suffer from the short-cycle problem that can affect OFB.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] If the IV/nonce is random, then they can be combined with the counter using any invertible operation (concatenation, addition, or XOR) to produce the actual unique counter block for encryption.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] In case of a non-random nonce (such as a packet counter), the nonce and counter should be concatenated (e.g., storing the nonce in the upper 64 bits and the counter in the lower 64 bits of a 128-bit counter block).
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Simply adding or XORing the nonce and counter into a single value would break the security under a chosen-plaintext attack in many cases, since the attacker may be able to manipulate the entire IV–counter pair to cause a collision.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Once an attacker controls the IV–counter pair and plaintext, XOR of the ciphertext with the known plaintext would yield a value that, when XORed with the ciphertext of the other block sharing the same IV–counter pair, would decrypt that block.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Note that the nonce in this diagram is equivalent to the initialization vector (IV) in the other diagrams.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] However, if the offset/location information is corrupt, it will be impossible to partially recover such data due to the dependence on byte offset.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] "Error propagation" properties describe how a decryption behaves during bit errors, i.e. how error in one bit cascades to different decrypted bits.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Bit errors may occur intentionally in attacks or randomly due to transmission errors.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] For modern authenticated encryption (AEAD) or protocols with message authentication codes chained in MAC-Then-Encrypt order, any bit error should completely abort decryption and must not generate any specific bit errors to decryptor.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] I.e. if decryption succeeded, there should not be any bit error.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] As such error propagation is less important subject in modern cipher modes than in traditional confidentiality-only modes.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] It might be observed, for example, that a one-block error in the transmitted ciphertext would result in a one-block error in the reconstructed plaintext for ECB mode encryption, while in CBC mode such an error would affect two blocks.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Some felt that such resilience was desirable in the face of random errors (e.g., line noise), while others argued that error correcting increased the scope for attackers to maliciously tamper with a message.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] However, when proper integrity protection is used, such an error will result (with high probability) in the entire message being rejected.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] If resistance to random error is desirable, error-correcting codes should be applied to the ciphertext before transmission.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Many more modes of operation for block ciphers have been suggested.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Some have been accepted, fully described (even standardized), and are in use.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Others have been found insecure, and should never be used.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Still others don't categorize as confidentiality, authenticity, or authenticated encryption – for example key feedback mode and Davies–Meyer hashing.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] NIST maintains a list of proposed modes for block ciphers at *Modes Development*.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Disk encryption often uses special purpose modes specifically designed for the application.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Tweakable narrow-block encryption modes (LRW, XEX, and XTS) and wide-block encryption modes (CMC and EME) are designed to securely encrypt sectors of a disk (see disk encryption theory).
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Many modes use an initialization vector (IV) which, depending on the mode, may have requirements such as being only used once (a nonce) or being unpredictable ahead of its publication, etc.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Reusing an IV with the same key in CTR, GCM or OFB mode results in XORing the same keystream with two or more plaintexts, a clear misuse of a stream, with a catastrophic loss of security.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Deterministic authenticated encryption modes such as the NIST Key Wrap algorithm and the SIV (RFC 5297) AEAD mode do not require an IV as an input, and return the same ciphertext and authentication tag every time for a given plaintext and key.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Other IV misuse-resistant modes such as AES-GCM-SIV benefit from an IV input, for example in the maximum amount of data that can be safely encrypted with one key, while not failing catastrophically if the same IV is used multiple times.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Block ciphers can also be used in other cryptographic protocols.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] They are generally used in modes of operation similar to the block modes described here.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] As with all protocols, to be cryptographically secure, care must be taken to design these modes of operation correctly.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] There are several schemes which use a block cipher to build a cryptographic hash function.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] See one-way compression function for descriptions of several such methods.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generators (CSPRNGs) can also be built using block ciphers.
[src:authenticated-encryption/block-cipher-mode-of-operation] Message authentication codes (MACs) are often built from block ciphers.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] The two building blocks of the construction, the algorithms Poly1305 and ChaCha20, were both independently designed, in 2005 and 2008, by Daniel J.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] In March 2013, a proposal was made to the IETF TLS working group to include Salsa20, a winner of the eSTREAM competition to replace the aging RC4-based ciphersuites.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] A discussion followed in the IETF TLS mailing list with various enhancement suggestions, including using Chacha20 instead of Salsa20 and using a universal hashing based MAC for performance.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] Shortly after the IETF's adoption of ChaCha20 and Poly1305 for TLS, the combined AEAD mode was added to OpenSSH via the`chacha20-poly1305@openssh.com` authenticated encryption cipher but kept the original 64-bit counter and 64-bit nonce for the ChaCha20 algorithm.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] In 2015, the AEAD algorithm was standardized in RFC 7539 and in RFC 7634 to be used in IPsec.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] The same year, it was integrated by Cloudflare as an alternative ciphersuite.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] In 2016 RFC 7905 describes how to use it in the TLS 1.2 and DTLS 1.2 protocols.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] In June 2018, RFC 7539 was updated and replaced by RFC 8439.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] The ChaCha20-Poly1305 algorithm takes as input a 256-bit key and a 96-bit nonce to encrypt a plaintext, with a ciphertext expansion of 128-bit (the tag size).
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] In the ChaCha20-Poly1305 construction, ChaCha20 is used to derive a key stream that is XORed with the plaintext.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] The ciphertext and the associated data is then authenticated using a variant of Poly1305 that first encodes the two strings into one.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] The way that a cipher and a one time authenticator are combined is precisely identical to AES-GCM construction in how the first block is used to seed the authenticator and how the ciphertext is then authenticated with a 16-byte tag.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] The main external difference with ChaCha20 is its 64 byte (512 bit) block size, in comparison to 16 bytes (128 bit) with both AES-128 and AES-256.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] The larger block size enables higher performance on modern CPUs and allows for larger streams before the 32 bit counter overflows.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] The XChaCha20-Poly1305 construction is an extended 192-bit nonce variant of the ChaCha20-Poly1305 construction, using XChaCha20 instead of ChaCha20.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] When choosing nonces at random, the XChaCha20-Poly1305 construction allows for better security than the original construction.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] The draft attempt to standardize the construction expired in July 2020.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] Salsa20-Poly1305 and XSalsa20-Poly1305 are variants of the ChaCha20-Poly1305 and XChaCha20-Poly1305 algorithms, using Salsa20 and XSalsa20 in place of ChaCha20 and XChaCha20.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] They are implemented in NaCl and libsodium but not standardized.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] The variants using ChaCha are preferred in practice as they provide better diffusion per round than Salsa.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] ChaCha20 can be replaced with its reduced-round variants ChaCha12 and ChaCha8, yielding ChaCha12-Poly1305 and ChaCha8-Poly1305.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] The same modification can be applied to XChaCha20-Poly1305.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] These are implemented by the RustCrypto team and not standardized.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] ChaCha20-Poly1305 is used in IPsec, SSH, TLS 1.2, DTLS 1.2, TLS 1.3, WireGuard, S/MIME 4.0, OTRv4 and multiple other protocols and implemented in OpenSSL and libsodium.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] Additionally, the algorithm is used in the backup software Borg in order to provide standard data encryption and in the copy-on-write filesystem Bcachefs for the purpose of optional whole filesystem encryption.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] It's also one of the encryption traffic methods of V2Ray.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] ChaCha20-Poly1305 usually offers better performance than the more prevalent AES-GCM algorithm, except on systems where the CPU(s) have the AES-NI instruction set extension.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] As a result, ChaCha20-Poly1305 is sometimes preferred over AES-GCM due to its similar levels of security and in certain use cases involving mobile devices, which mostly use ARM-based CPUs.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] Because ChaCha20-Poly1305 has less overhead than AES-GCM, ChaCha20-Poly1305 on mobile devices may consume less power than AES-GCM.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] The ChaCha20-Poly1305 construction is generally secure in the standard model and the ideal permutation model, for the single- and multi-user setting.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] However, similarly to GCM, the security relies on choosing a unique nonce for every message encrypted.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] Compared to AES-GCM, implementations of ChaCha20-Poly1305 are less vulnerable to timing attacks.
[src:authenticated-encryption/chacha20-poly1305] To be noted, when the SSH protocol uses ChaCha20-Poly1305 as underlying primitive, it is vulnerable to the Terrapin attack.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] In cryptography, **Galois/Counter Mode** (**GCM**) is a mode of operation for symmetric-key cryptographic block ciphers.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] The proposal was first published in 2007.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] The GCM algorithm belongs to the class of authenticated encryption with associated data (AEAD) methods.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Given a key K , plaintext P , and associated data $AD$ , GCM encrypts P to produce ciphertext C and an authentication tag T .
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] T is computed from the ciphertext and the unencrypted associated data.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] A recipient who knows K can use the tag to verify that neither the ciphertext nor the associated data had been modified, and then decrypt the ciphertext to recover the plaintext.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] GCM uses a block cipher with a block size of 128 bits, (commonly AES-128) run in counter mode for encryption and uses arithmetic in the Galois field GF(2128) to compute the authentication tag, hence its name.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Different block cipher modes of operation can have significantly different performance with the same block cipher.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] As a counter mode, GCM blocks are independent.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] This allows encryption and decryption to be parallelized, in contrast to modes like cipher block chaining (CBC) where each block relies on the previous one.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] GCM was explicitly designed to be patent-free.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] GCM operates as a counter mode block cipher to produce ciphertext.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] For authentication, the ciphertext blocks are treated as coefficients of a polynomial evaluated at a key-dependent point *H* using finite field arithmetic.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] The result is then encrypted, producing an authentication tag that can be used to verify the integrity of the data, so that the encrypted text has the IV, ciphertext, and authentication tag.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] GCM combines the counter mode of encryption with the Galois mode of authentication.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] The central feature is the ease of parallel computation of the Galois field multiplication used for authentication.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] This feature has higher throughput than encryption algorithms like CBC that use chaining modes.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] The authentication tag is constructed by feeding blocks of data into the GHASH function and encrypting the result.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] The second form is an efficient iterative algorithm (each $X_{i}$ depends on $X_{i-1}$ ) produced by applying Horner's method to the first.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Only the final $X_{m+n+1}$ stays an output.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] GCM was designed by John Viega and David A.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] McGrew as a development based on earlier counter-mode authenticated encryption designs, including Carter–Wegman counter mode (CWC mode).
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] In November 2007, NIST announced the release of NIST Special Publication 800-38D *Recommendation for Block Cipher Modes of Operation: Galois/Counter Mode (GCM) and GMAC*, making GCM and GMAC official standards.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] GCM mode is used in the IEEE 802.1AE (MACsec) Ethernet security, WPA3-Enterprise Wi-Fi security protocol, IEEE 802.11ad (also dubbed WiGig), ANSI (INCITS) Fibre Channel Security Protocols (FC-SP), IEEE P1619.1 tape storage, IETF IPsec standards, SSH, TLS 1.2 and TLS 1.3.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] AES-GCM is included in the NSA Suite B Cryptography and its latest replacement in 2018 Commercial National Security Algorithm (CNSA) suite.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] GCM mode is used in the SoftEther VPN server and client, as well as OpenVPN, where AES-GCM ciphers are available via configuration and cipher negotiation since version 2.4.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] GCM requires one block cipher operation and one 128-bit multiplication in the Galois field for each block (128 bits) of encrypted and authenticated data.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] The block cipher operations are pipelined or parallelized; the multiplication operations are pipelined and can be parallelized (either by parallelizing the actual operation, by adapting Horner's method per the original NIST submission, or both).
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Intel has added the PCLMULQDQ instruction, which supports carry-less multiplication used in GCM implementations.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] In 2011, SPARC added the XMULX and XMULXHI instructions, which also perform 64 × 64-bit carry-less multiplication.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] In 2015, SPARC added the XMPMUL instruction, which performs XOR multiplication of much larger values, up to 2048 × 2048-bit input values, producing a 4096-bit result.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] These instructions enable fast multiplication over GF(2*n*) and can be used with any field representation.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Performance results are published for GCM on a number of platforms.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Käsper and Schwabe described a "Faster and Timing-Attack Resistant AES-GCM" that achieves 10.68 cycles per byte of AES-GCM authenticated encryption on 64-bit Intel processors.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Dai et al. report 3.5 cycles per byte for the same algorithm when using Intel's AES-NI and PCLMULQDQ instructions.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Shay Gueron and Vlad Krasnov achieved 2.47 cycles per byte on the third-generation Intel processors.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Appropriate patches were prepared for the OpenSSL and NSS libraries.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] When both authentication and encryption need to be performed on a message, interleaving those operations using instruction-level parallelism can increase performance.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] This process is called function stitching, and while in principle it can be applied to any combination of cryptographic algorithms, GCM supports parallel computation which can simplify optimization on some processors.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Manley and Gregg show the ease of optimizing when using function stitching with GCM.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] They present a program generator that takes an annotated C version of a cryptographic algorithm and generates code that runs well on the target processor.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] GCM has been criticized in the embedded world (for example, by Silicon Labs) because the parallel processing is not suited for performant use of cryptographic hardware engines.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] As a result, GCM reduces the performance of encryption for some of the most performance-sensitive devices.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Specialized hardware accelerators for ChaCha20-Poly1305 are less complex compared to AES accelerators.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] GCM is proven to be secure in the concrete security model.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] It is secure when it is used with a block cipher that is indistinguishable from a random permutation; however, security depends on choosing a unique initialization vector for every encryption performed with the same key (*see* stream cipher attack).
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] For any given key and initialization vector value, GCM is limited to encrypting 239−256 bits of plain text (64 GiB).
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] NIST Special Publication 800-38D includes guidelines for initialization vector choice and limits the number of possible initialization vector values for a single key.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] As the security assurance of GCM degrades with more data being processed using the same key, the total number of blocks of plaintext and AD protected during the lifetime of a single key should be limited by 264.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] The authentication strength depends on the length of the authentication tag, like with all symmetric message authentication codes.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Using shorter authentication tags with GCM is discouraged.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] The bit-length of the tag, denoted *t*, is a security parameter.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] In general, *t* may be any one of the following five values: 128, 120, 112, 104, or 96.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] For certain applications, *t* may be 64 or 32, but the use of these two tag lengths constrains the length of the input data and the lifetime of the key.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Like with any message authentication code, if the adversary chooses a *t*-bit tag at random, it is expected to be correct for given data with probability measure 2−*t*.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] With GCM, however, an adversary can increase their likelihood of success by choosing tags with *n* words—the total length of the ciphertext plus any added authenticated data (AAD)—with probability measure 2−*t* by a factor of *n*.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] However, these best tags are still dominated by the algorithm's survival measure 1 − *n*⋅2−*t* for arbitrarily large *t*.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Moreover, GCM is not well-suited for use with short tag-lengths or long messages.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Ferguson and Saarinen independently described how an attacker can perform best attacks against GCM authentication, which meets the lower bound on its security.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Ferguson showed that, if *n* denotes the total number of blocks in the encoding (the input to the GHASH function), then there is a method of constructing a targeted ciphertext forgery that is expected to succeed with a probability of approximately *n*⋅2−*t*.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] If the tag length *t* is shorter than 128, then each successful forgery in this attack increases the probability that subsequent targeted forgeries will succeed, and leaks information about the hash subkey *H*.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Eventually, *H* may be compromised entirely, at which point the authentication assurance is completely lost.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Independent of this attack, an adversary may try to systematically guess many different tags for a given input to authenticated decryption and thereby increase the probability that one (or more) of them, eventually, will be considered valid.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] For this reason, the system or protocol that implements GCM should watch and, if necessary, limit the number of unsuccessful verification attempts for each key.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Saarinen described GCM as having weak keys, offering some added analysis into how polynomial hash-based authentication works.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] More precisely, this work describes a particular way of forging a GCM message, given a valid GCM message, that works with probability of about *n*⋅2−128 for messages that are *n* × 128 bits long.
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] However, this work does not show a more effective attack than was previously known; the success probability in observation 1 of this paper matches that of lemma 2 from the INDOCRYPT 2004 analysis (setting *w* = 128 and *l* = *n* × 128).
[src:authenticated-encryption/counter-mode] Saarinen also described a GCM variant Sophie Germain Counter Mode (SGCM) based on Sophie Germain primes.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This article provides a simple model to follow when implementing solutions to protect data at rest.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Passwords should not be stored using reversible encryption - secure password hashing algorithms should be used instead.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Password Storage Cheat Sheet contains further guidance on storing passwords.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The first step in designing any application is to consider the overall architecture of the system, as this will have a huge impact on the technical implementation.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This process should begin with considering the threat model of the application (i.e, who you are trying to protect that data against).
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Note that many cloud environments provide these services, so these should be taken advantage of where possible.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Secrets Management Cheat Sheet contains further guidance on this topic.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Which layer(s) are most appropriate will depend on the threat model.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, hardware level encryption is effective at protecting against the physical theft of the server, but will provide no protection if an attacker is able to compromise the server remotely.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The best way to protect sensitive information is to not store it in the first place.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Although this applies to all kinds of information, it is most often applicable to credit card details, as they are highly desirable for attackers, and PCI DSS has such stringent requirements for how they must be stored.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Wherever possible, the storage of sensitive information should be avoided.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For symmetric encryption **AES** with a key that's at least **128 bits** (ideally **256 bits**) and a secure mode should be used as the preferred algorithm.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For asymmetric encryption, use elliptical curve cryptography (ECC) with a secure curve such as **Curve25519** as a preferred algorithm.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] If ECC is not available and **RSA** must be used, then ensure that the key is at least **2048 bits**.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Many other symmetric and asymmetric algorithms are available which have their own pros and cons, and they may be better or worse than AES or Curve25519 in specific use cases.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In some cases there may be regulatory requirements that limit the algorithms that can be used, such as FIPS 140-2 or PCI DSS.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] There are various modes that can be used to allow block ciphers (such as AES) to encrypt arbitrary amounts of data, in the same way that a stream cipher would.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] These modes have different security and performance characteristics, and a full discussion of them is outside the scope of this cheat sheet.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Some of the modes have requirements to generate secure initialisation vectors (IVs) and other attributes, but these should be handled automatically by the library.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where available, authenticated modes should always be used.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] These provide guarantees of the integrity and authenticity of the data, as well as confidentiality.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The most commonly used authenticated modes are **GCM** and **CCM**, which should be used as a first preference.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] If GCM or CCM are not available, then CTR mode or CBC mode should be used.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As these do not provide any guarantees about the authenticity of the data, separate authentication should be implemented, such as using the Encrypt-then-MAC technique.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] ECB should not be used outside of very specific circumstances.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For RSA, it is essential to enable Random Padding.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Random Padding is also known as OAEP or Optimal Asymmetric Encryption Padding.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This class of defense protects against Known Plain Text Attacks by adding randomness at the beginning of the payload.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Padding Schema of PKCS#1 is typically used in this case.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Random numbers (or strings) are needed for various security critical functionality, such as generating encryption keys, IVs, session IDs, CSRF tokens or password reset tokens.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As such, it is important that these are generated securely, and that it is not possible for an attacker to guess and predict them.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] It is generally not possible for computers to generate truly random numbers (without special hardware), so most systems and languages provide two different types of randomness.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Pseudo-Random Number Generators (PRNG) provide low-quality randomness that are much faster, and can be used for non-security related functionality (such as ordering results on a page, or randomising UI elements).
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, they **must not** be used for anything security critical, as it is often possible for attackers to guess or predict the output.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Cryptographically Secure Pseudo-Random Number Generators (CSPRNG) are designed to produce a much higher quality of randomness (more strictly, a greater amount of entropy), making them safe to use for security-sensitive functionality.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, they are slower and more CPU intensive, can end up blocking in some circumstances when large amounts of random data are requested.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As such, if large amounts of non-security related randomness are needed, they may not be appropriate.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The table below shows the recommended algorithms for each language, as well as insecure functions that should not be used.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Universally unique identifiers (UUIDs or GUIDs) are sometimes used as a quick way to generate random strings.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Although they can provide a reasonable source of randomness, this will depend on the type or version of the UUID that is created.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Specifically, version 1 UUIDs are comprised of a high precision timestamp and the MAC address of the system that generated them, so are **not random** (although they may be hard to guess, given the timestamp is to the nearest 100ns).
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Type 4 UUIDs are randomly generated, although whether this is done using a CSPRNG will depend on the implementation.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Unless this is known to be secure in the specific language or framework, the randomness of UUIDs should not be relied upon.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Applications should be designed to still be secure even if cryptographic controls fail.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Any information that is stored in an encrypted form should also be protected by additional layers of security.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Application should also not rely on the security of encrypted URL parameters, and should enforce strong access control to prevent unauthorised access to information.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Keys should be randomly generated using a cryptographically secure function, such as those discussed in the Secure Random Number Generation section.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Keys **should not** be based on common words or phrases, or on "random" characters generated by mashing the keyboard.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where multiple keys are used (such as data separate data-encrypting and key-encrypting keys), they should be fully independent from each other.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Once one of these criteria have been met, a new key should be generated and used for encrypting any new data.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Marking each item with the ID of the key that was used to encrypt it, and storing multiple keys to allow the old data to be decrypted.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The first option should generally be preferred, as it greatly simplifies both the application code and key management processes; however, it may not always be feasible.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Note that old keys should generally be stored for a certain period after they have been retired, in case old backups of copies of the data need to be decrypted.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] It is important that the code and processes required to rotate a key are in place **before** they are required, so that keys can be quickly rotated in the event of a compromise.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Additionally, processes should also be implemented to allow the encryption algorithm or library to be changed, in case a new vulnerability is found in the algorithm or implementation.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Securely storing cryptographic keys is one of the hardest problems to solve, as the application always needs to have some level of access to the keys in order to decrypt the data.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] While it may not be possible to fully protect the keys from an attacker who has fully compromised the application, a number of steps can be taken to make it harder for them to obtain the keys.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where available, the secure storage mechanisms provided by the operating system, framework or cloud service provider should be used.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] There are many advantages to using these types of secure storage over simply putting keys in configuration files.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In some cases none of these will be available, such as in a shared hosting environment, meaning that it is not possible to obtain a high degree of protection for any encryption keys.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Secrets Management Cheat Sheet provides more details on securely storing secrets.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where possible, encryption keys should be stored in a separate location from encrypted data.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, if the data is stored in a database, the keys should be stored in the filesystem.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This means that if an attacker only has access to one of these (for example through directory traversal or SQL injection), they cannot access both the keys and the data.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Depending on the architecture of the environment, it may be possible to store the keys and data on separate systems, which would provide a greater degree of isolation.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where possible, encryption keys should themselves be stored in an encrypted form.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For this to be effective, the KEK must be stored separately from the DEK.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The encrypted DEK can be stored with the data, but will only be usable if an attacker is able to also obtain the KEK, which is stored on another system.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The KEK should also be at least as strong as the DEK.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The envelope encryption guidance from Google contains further details on how to manage DEKs and KEKs.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In simpler application architectures (such as shared hosting environments) where the KEK and DEK cannot be stored separately, there is limited value to this approach, as an attacker is likely to be able to obtain both of the keys at the same time.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, it can provide an additional barrier to unskilled attackers.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] A key derivation function (KDF) could be used to generate a KEK from user-supplied input (such a passphrase), which would then be used to encrypt a randomly generated DEK.
[src:authenticated-encryption/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This allows the KEK to be easily changed (when the user changes their passphrase), without needing to re-encrypt the data (as the DEK remains the same).
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] In cryptography, a **padding oracle attack** is an attack which uses the padding validation of a cryptographic message to decrypt the ciphertext.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] In cryptography, variable-length plaintext messages often have to be padded (expanded) to be compatible with the underlying cryptographic primitive.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] The attack relies on having a "padding oracle" which freely responds to queries about whether a message is correctly padded or not.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] The information could be directly given, or leaked through a side-channel.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] The earliest well-known attack that uses a padding oracle is Bleichenbacher's attack of 1998, which attacks RSA with PKCS #1 v1.5 padding.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] The term "padding oracle" appeared in literature in 2002, after Serge Vaudenay's attack on the CBC mode decryption used within symmetric block ciphers.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] Variants of both attacks continue to find success more than one decade after their original publication.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] In 1998, Daniel Bleichenbacher published a seminal paper on what became known as Bleichenbacher's attack (also known as "million message attack").
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] The attack uses a padding oracle against RSA with PKCS #1 v1.5 padding, but it does not include the term.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] Later authors have classified his attack as a padding oracle attack.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] Manger (2001) reports an attack on the replacement for PKCS #1 v1.5 padding, PKCS #1 v2.0 "OAEP".
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] In symmetric cryptography, the padding oracle attack can be applied to the CBC mode of operation.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] Leaked data on padding validity can allow attackers to decrypt (and sometimes encrypt) messages through the oracle using the oracle's key, without knowing the encryption key.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] Compared to Bleichenbacher's attack on RSA with PKCS #1 v1.5, Vaudenay's attack on CBC is much more efficient.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] Both attacks target crypto systems commonly used for the time: CBC is the original mode used in Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) and had continued to be supported in TLS.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] A number of mitigations have been performed to prevent the decryption software from acting as an oracle, but newer attacks based on timing have repeatedly revived this oracle.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] TLS 1.2 introduces a number of authenticated encryption with additional data modes that do not rely on CBC.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] The standard implementation of CBC decryption in block ciphers is to decrypt all ciphertext blocks, validate the padding, remove the PKCS7 padding, and return the message's plaintext.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] If the server allows an attacker to hand over arbitrary data, the attacker can use the server as a padding oracle to decrypt (and sometimes encrypt) messages.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] The only way to prevent this attack is to make sure that the attacker cannot manipulate the data handed over to the algorithm, e.g. by only accepting messages which are secured with a digital signature or message authentication code which the attacker cannot forge.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] As depicted above, CBC decryption XORs each plaintext block with the previous block.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] As a result, a single-byte modification in block $C_{1}$ will make a corresponding change to a single byte in $P_{2}$ .
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] Suppose the attacker has two ciphertext blocks $C_{1},C_{2}$ and wants to decrypt the second block to get plaintext $P_{2}$ .
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] The attacker changes the last byte of $C_{1}$ (creating $C_{1}'$ ) and sends $(IV,C_{1}',C_{2})$ to the server.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] The server then returns whether or not the padding of the last decrypted block ( $P_{2}'$ ) is correct (a valid PKCS#7 padding).
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] If the padding is correct, the attacker now knows that the last byte of $D_{K}(C_{2})\oplus C_{1}'$ is $\mathrm {0x01}$ , the last two bytes are 0x02, the last three bytes are 0x03, …, or the last eight bytes are 0x08.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] The attacker can modify the second-last byte (flip any bit) to ensure that the last byte is 0x01.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] (Alternatively, the attacker can flip earlier bytes and binary search for the position to identify the padding.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] For example, if modifying the third-last byte is correct, but modifying the second-last byte is incorrect, then the last two bytes are known to be 0x02, allowing both of them to be decrypted.) Therefore, the last byte of $D_{K}(C_{2})$ equals $C_{1}'\oplus \mathrm {0x01}$ .
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] If the padding is incorrect, the attacker can change the last byte of $C_{1}'$ to the next possible value.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] At most, the attacker will need to make 256 attempts to find the last byte of $P_{2}$ , 255 attempts for every possible byte (256 possible, minus one by pigeonhole principle), plus one additional attempt to eliminate an ambiguous padding.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] After determining the last byte of $P_{2}$ , the attacker can use the same technique to obtain the second-to-last byte of $P_{2}$ .
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] The attacker then uses the same approach described above, this time modifying the second-to-last byte until the padding is correct (0x02, 0x02).
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] If a block consists of 128 bits (AES, for example), which is 16 bytes, the attacker will obtain plaintext $P_{2}$ in no more than 256⋅16 = 4096 attempts.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] This is significantly faster than the $2^{128}$ attempts required to bruteforce a 128-bit key.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] CBC-R turns a decryption oracle into an encryption oracle, and is primarily demonstrated against padding oracles.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] To generate a ciphertext that is N blocks long, attacker must perform N numbers of padding oracle attacks.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] These attacks are chained together so that proper plaintext is constructed in reverse order, from end of message (CN) to beginning message (*C*0, IV).
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] In each step, padding oracle attack is used to construct the IV to the previous chosen ciphertext.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] The CBC-R attack will not work against an encryption scheme that authenticates ciphertext (using a message authentication code or similar) before decrypting.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] The original attack against CBC was published in 2002 by Serge Vaudenay.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] Concrete instantiations of the attack were later realised against SSL and IPSec.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] It was also applied to several web frameworks, including JavaServer Faces, Ruby on Rails and ASP.NET as well as other software, such as the Steam gaming client.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] In 2012 it was shown to be effective against PKCS 11 cryptographic tokens.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] While these earlier attacks were fixed by most TLS implementors following its public announcement, a new variant, the Lucky Thirteen attack, published in 2013, used a timing side-channel to re-open the vulnerability even in implementations that had previously been fixed.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] As of early 2014, the attack is no longer considered a threat in real-life operation, though it is still workable in theory (see signal-to-noise ratio) against a certain class of machines.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] An attack called POODLE (late 2014) combines both a downgrade attack (to SSL 3.0) with a padding oracle attack on the older, insecure protocol to enable compromise of the transmitted data.
[src:authenticated-encryption/padding-oracle-attack] In May 2016 it has been revealed in CVE-2016-2107 that the fix against Lucky Thirteen in OpenSSL introduced another timing-based padding oracle.
